Design spec:

NAVIGATION CONTROLS:
A fixed navigation widget — always visible, does not scroll.
Position: top right corner of the diff table container.

Widget layout:
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│  ↑  Change 3 of 25  ↓      │
└─────────────────────────────┘

- Up arrow button:    jump to previous change
- Down arrow button:  jump to next change
- Counter text:       "Change X of Y"
                      X = current change (1-based)
                      Y = total changes (added + deleted + modified)
- Keyboard shortcuts: [ and ] or Alt+Up / Alt+Down
                      whichever feels natural

BEHAVIOUR:
- On first load: no change selected, counter shows "25 changes"
- First press of ↓: jumps to first change, counter shows "Change 1 of 25"
- Subsequent ↓: jumps to next change in document order
- At last change: ↓ wraps to first change
- First press of ↑: jumps to last change (wrap from top)
- At first change: ↑ wraps to last change
- "Jump" means: scroll the row into view, centred vertically
  Use element.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'center' })

CURRENT CHANGE HIGHLIGHT:
The currently selected change row gets an extra visual indicator
on top of its existing colour (amber/green/red):
- A 3px left border in bright white or bright accent colour
- Or a subtle box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 2px rgba(255,255,255,0.4)
This makes it obvious which change you're currently viewing.
Unchanged rows are never selected by navigation.

CHANGE INDEX:
Build a changeIndex array when DiffResult is received:
const changeIndex = unifiedRows
  .map((row, i) => ({ row, i }))
  .filter(({ row }) => row.type !== 'unchanged')
  .map(({ i }) => i)

Navigation moves through changeIndex positions.
Each entry points to the array index of a changed row.

ROW REFS:
Assign a React ref to each changed row's <tr> element.
Use an array of refs: rowRefs[i] = useRef<HTMLTableRowElement>

On navigation:
  const targetIndex = changeIndex[currentChangePos]
  rowRefs[targetIndex].current?.scrollIntoView({
    behavior: 'smooth',
    block: 'center'
  })

